%html
	%head
		%title CocoaPods: The Objective-C Library Manager
		%link{:rel => "stylesheet", :type => "text/css", :href => "stylesheets/css/cocoapods.css", :media => "screen"}/
		%link{:rel => "stylesheet", :type => "text/css", :href => "stylesheets/prettify.css", :media => "screen"}/
		%link{:rel => "shortcut icon", :href => "favicon.ico"}
		= analytics

	%body
		.container
			.header
				.logo
				.breadcrumb
					%a{ :href => "http://cocoapods.org/" } CocoaPods
					/ %a{ :href => "http://cocoapods.org/" } Cocoa<em>Pods</em>
				%form{:class => "search-form", :id => "search", :onkeypress => "return event.keyCode != 13;"}
					%fieldset
						.platform
							%input{:value => "", :type => "radio", :id => "platform_either", :name => "platform", :checked => (@platform == :either)}/
							%label{:class => "left", :for => "platform_either"} <span>Either OS</span>
							%input{:value => "on:osx on:ios", :type => "radio", :id => "platform_both", :name => "platform", :checked => (@platform == :both)}/
							%label{:class =>"middle", :for =>"platform_both"} <span>iOS &amp; OSX</span>
							%input{:value => "on:ios", :type => "radio", :id => "platform_ios", :name => "platform", :checked => (@platform == :ios)}/
							%label{:class => "middle", :for => "platform_ios"} <span>iOS</span>
							%input{:value => "on:osx", :type => "radio", :id => "platform_osx", :name => "platform", :checked => (@platform == :osx)}/
							%label{:class => "right", :for => "platform_osx"} <span>OSX</span>
						%input{:type => "search", :id => "pod_search", :placeholder => "pod name, version, author, deps…", :class => "query", :autofocus => true, :autocomplete => "off"}/
						%a{ :href => "#", :class => "reset-search", :style => "display:none" } Reset search
			.sidebar
				.masthead
					%p
						The best way to manage library 
						dependencies in Objective-C 
						projects.
				/ .intro
				/ 	%p
				/ 		Specify the libraries for your project in an easy to edit text file. Then use 
				/ 		CocoaPods to resolve all dependencies, fetch the source, and set up your 
				/ 		Xcode workspace.
				%nav
					%h2 Issues & Code
					%ul
						%li
							%a{:href => "https://github.com/CocoaPods/CocoaPods/issues"} Submit an issue
						%li
							%a{:href => "https://github.com/CocoaPods/CocoaPods"} Github Repository
					%h2 News & Infos
					%ul
						%li
							%a{:href => "http://docs.cocoapods.org/"} Documentation
						%li
							%a{:href =>"http://groups.google.com/group/cocoapods"} Mailing List
						%li
							%a{:href => "https://github.com/CocoaPods/CocoaPods/wiki"} Browse the wiki
						%li
							%a{:href => "http://feeds.cocoapods.org/new-pods.rss"} New Pods RSS Feed
			%article.main-content
				#search
					// %a{ :href => "#", :class => "reset-search", :style => "display:none" } Clear Results
					.no_results{:style => "display:none"}
						No pods found.
					.allocations
						%ol.shown
						%ol.more more
						%ol.hidden
					.results
				%section#install
					%h2 Install
					%p
						CocoaPods is distributed as a <a href="http://rubygems.org/gems/cocoapods">ruby gem</a>, 
						installing it is as easy as running the following commands in the terminal:
					%pre.prettyprint
						:preserve
							$ [sudo] gem install cocoapods
							$ pod setup
					%p
						Now that you’ve got CocoaPods installed it’s time to 
						<a href="#get_started">get started</a>.

				%section#get_started
					%h2 Get started
					%p
						Search for pods by name and description.
					%p
						Then list the dependencies in a text file named Podfile in 
						your Xcode project directory:
					%pre.prettyprint
						:preserve
							$ edit Podfile
							platform :ios
							pod 'JSONKit',       '~> 1.4'
							pod 'Reachability',  '~> 3.0.0'
					%p
						Now you can install the dependencies in your project:
					%pre.prettyprint
						$ pod install
					%p
						Make sure to always open the Xcode workspace instead of the project 
						file when building your project:
					%pre.prettyprint
						$ open App.xcworkspace
					%h3 How to create a pod
					%p
						Sometimes CocoaPods doesn’t yet have a pod for one of your dependencies. 
						Fortunately, creating a pod is pretty easy:
					%pre.prettyprint
						:preserve
							$ pod spec create Peanut
							$ edit Peanut.podspec
							$ pod spec lint Peanut.podspec
					%p
						When you’re done, please <a href="https://github.com/CocoaPods/CocoaPods/issues">create a ticket</a> 
						and upload the pod. You can also fork the <a href="https://github.com/CocoaPods/Specs">CocoaPods specs</a> 
						GitHub repository and send a pull request. We really love contributions!

				%section#contribute
					%h2 Contribute
					%p
						We’re developing CocoaPods on GitHub. There’s a repository for the 
						<a href="https://github.com/CocoaPods/CocoaPods">CocoaPods tool</a> and one for the 
						<a href="https://github.com/CocoaPods/Specs">pods specs</a>. It’s easy and really gratifying 
						to contribute patches or pods, you even get push access when one of your specs or patches is accepted.
					%p
						Follow <a href="http://twitter.com/CocoaPods">CocoaPods</a> on Twitter to get up to date 
						information about what’s going on in the CocoaPods world.
					%p
						Please report any problems with CocoaPods to the <a href="http://github.com/CocoaPods/CocoaPods/issues">CocoaPods issues page</a>.
